October 2015

Volume 30 Number 10

The Work= ing Programmer - How To Be MEAN: Express Install

By Ted Neward | October 2015

The MongoDB, Express, AngularJS, Node.js (MEAN) stack is an alternative = =E2=80=9CWeb stack=E2=80=9D (some say complementary, others say supplementa= ry) to the ASP.NET stack to which .NET developers are accustomed. This inst= allment marks the third in the series in which I=E2=80=99ll cover the Expre= ss library that handles HTTP processing on the server.

In the last installment (msdn.microsoft.com/magazine/mt422588), I showed how to install a Node.js application into Microsoft Azure. Bec= ause doing this is essentially just committing to a Git repository (and the= n pushing those commits to the Azure remote repository), I=E2=80=99ll leave= those out in this and future columns, at least until I start talking to ot= her services (such as MongoDB) on the Azure platform. Alternatively, you ca= n run all the examples on local machines in order to follow along. Azure ce= rtainly isn=E2=80=99t required (at least, not until I start talking about p= ushing to production).

Get on the= Express

All train puns aside, Express is a fairly straightforward library. It=E2= =80=99s easy to work with, once you embrace =E2=80=9Cthe Node.js way.=E2=80= =9D Just to keep the cognitive load light, I=E2=80=99ll start from scratch = (relatively speaking). I=E2=80=99ll assume you have a brand-new Azure site = (the results of a successful =E2=80=9Cazure site create=E2=80=94git=E2=80= =9D command) and a simple Express application up and running.

In the first installment (msdn.microsoft.com/magazine/mt185576), I mentioned npm, the Node Package Manager. This is the library and dep= endency manager for all Node applications. It=E2=80=99s similar to the role= NuGet plays in the Microsoft .NET Framework world. In fact, both were insp= ired by Ruby gems, so they share a number of the same characteristics.

As it turns out, for all of its information, npm depends on a JSON file = that contains all of the dependencies=E2=80=94production and development-on= ly packages=E2=80=94on a single file called package.json. So a logical firs= t step is to create the file with Express as a dependency, as shown in Figure 1.

Figure 1 Create a File with Express as a Dependency

JavaScript
{
  "name": "MSDN-MEAN",
  "version": "0.0.1",
  "description": "Testing out building a MEAN app from scratch",
  "main": "app.js",
  "scripts": {},
  "author": "Ted Neward",
  "license": "ISC",
  "dependencies": {
    "express": "^4.9.8",
    "lodash": "^2.4.1",
    "serve-static": "^1.7.0"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
  }
}

The contents of this file are mostly self-explanatory, but there are a f= ew things worth pointing out. First, you=E2=80=99d often maintain this file= by hand (although there are some tools that will manage it for you). That= =E2=80=99s in keeping with the =E2=80=9Ctext editor and command line=E2=80= =9D mentality of the Node.js world. As a result, would-be Node developers s= hould be comfortable editing by hand, regardless of the availability of any= tools. Second, there are two sets of dependencies here. The dependencies a= re the packages the npm should install in a production-type environment. Th= e devDependencies are packages used solely by developers.

For now, the easiest way to think about this is dependencies will be ins= talled when the app is pushed (through Git) to Azure. The devDependencies a= re installed (along with the contents of dependencies) when installing pack= ages on a developer laptop, as shown in Figure 2


Figure 2 Install Your Dependencies

Speaking of which, you should do that now. With just the package.json fi= le in the current directory, enter =E2=80=9Cnpm install=E2=80=9D at the com= mand line and watch npm pull down express, lodash (a handy library of funct= ions and methods, including some functional tools like map and filter, as w= ell as extensions to arrays and objects), and serve-static (which I=E2=80= =99ll discuss later) onto your local machine.

 Like NuGet, npm installs not just the package, but all its depende= ncies, as well. This is what causes the tree display in the terminal. For l= arge umbrella packages that incorporate a large number of popular packages,= this display can get quite long. The npm tool also notes that I=E2=80=99ve= left out two entries in my package.json: the repository field where this p= ackage comes from and the README data. These are used mostly for npm packag= es installed into the central npm library. I don=E2=80=99t find them partic= ularly appropriate for an application, but there=E2=80=99s certainly no har= m in having them if you prefer warning-less npm activity.

As this series continues, I will add addi=C2=ADtional packages to packag= e.json, so you should periodically run =E2=80=9Cnpm install=E2=80=9D to get= the new packages. As a matter of fact, notice in the install output tree f= or express, the debug package (which I used in the last installment) is a d= ependency, but I didn=E2=80=99t put it into the package.json file directly.= It=E2=80=99s been my habit that my package.json file should explicitly lis= t all dependencies I use directly (as opposed to those used by the librarie= s, but never called directly), so go ahead and add it to package.json and d= o another =E2=80=9Cnpm install=E2=80=9D:

JavaScript
"dependencies": {
  "debug": "^2.2.0",
  "express": "^4.9.8",
  "lodash": "^2.4.1",
  "serve-static": "^1.7.0"
},

This way I know which version of debug I=E2=80=99m actually using (as op= posed to what version Express is using), in case that difference becomes im= portant. By the way, the traditional way to install a library (now that you= know what the file format looks like) is to use =E2=80=9Cnpm install <p= ackage> --save.=E2=80=9D Using the =E2=80=9C--save=E2=80=9D argument cau= ses npm to modify the package.json file (as opposed to just installing it w= ithout record).

In fact, if you do an =E2=80=9Cnpm install express --save,=E2=80=9D npm = will update the express entry to the latest version (which, as of this writ= ing, is 4.13.3), even though it=E2=80=99s already there. There=E2=80=99s ye= t a third way, using another package called yeoman to scaffold out an Expre= ss app, but part of the goal here is to understand all the moving parts in = MEAN, so I=E2=80=99ll leave that for later.

Hello, Express

Once the Express bits are installed, it=E2=80=99s a simple matter to wri= te the ubiquitous =E2=80=9Chello world=E2=80=9D in Express. In a file calle= d app.js (because that=E2=80=99s what package.json has as its entry for =E2= =80=9Cmain=E2=80=9D), the code in Figure 3 provides the si= mple-yet-necessary homage to the Gods of Computer Science.

Figure 3 The Code for the Hello World Express

JavaScript
// Load modules
var express =3D require('express');
var debug =3D require('debug')('app');
// Create express instance
var app =3D express();
// Set up a simple route
app.get('/', function (req, res) {
  debug("/ requested");
  res.send('Hello World!');
});
// Start the server
var port =3D process.env.PORT || 3000;
debug("We picked up",port,"for the port");
var server =3D app.listen(port, function () {
  var host =3D server.address().ad=
dress;
  var port =3D server.address().po=
rt;
  console.log('Example app listening at http://%s:%s', host, port);
});

The first two lines are the require calls you saw in the previous instal= lment, which is how Node.js loads modules at the moment. This will change i= n ECMAScript 6, once that=E2=80=99s ratified and shipped. These give you ac= cess to the Express and debug packages, respectively. The Express module fe= tched by require is actually a function that, when called, yields the Expre= ss app itself=E2=80=94hence, it goes into app (by convention).

The next line is what Express calls a route. This is similar in many res= pects to the routing tables more popular in ASP.NET and ASP.NET MVC of late= . This maps a request verb (get) with a relative URL path (=E2=80=9C/=E2=80= =9D in this case) to a function. In this case, it=E2=80=99s an anony=C2=ADm= ous function literal that responds with =E2=80=9CHello World.=E2=80=9D Note= the function also uses the debug object to spew out a quick line after rec= eiving a request.

Last, the code checks the current environment to see if there=E2=80=99s = a PORT environment variable specified (which there will be in Azure). If no= t, it assigns 3000 to port. Then the app object is told to listen, which is= a blocking call. It will execute the anonymous function literal passed in = when it begins listening. Then the process will just wait for an incoming r= equest. Assuming the request is for =E2=80=9C/,=E2=80=9D it replies with = =E2=80=9CHello World.=E2=80=9D

D= ebug, Express and You

As mentioned in the previous installment, the debug output doesn=E2=80= =99t show up unless the DEBUG environment variable is set to the same strin= g used in the require step. In this case, that=E2=80=99s app. Express also = uses debug, and if DEBUG is set to =E2=80=9C*,=E2=80=9D then all of the Exp= ress diagnostic output will also display. It=E2=80=99s probably a bit too v= oluminous to use for debugging on a regular basis, but it can be helpful to= see it scroll by in the early days of working with Express. That will help= give you a sense of the various parts and what=E2=80=99s being invoked whe= n. There=E2=80=99s an example of its output (with a few requests) shown in = Figure 4.


Figure 4 Express with Debug Logging

To turn debugging off, simply set DEBUG to nothing. To view more than on= e debug stream, but not all of them, just comma-=C2=ADseparate the names:

JavaScript
DEBUG=3Dapp,express:router,express:router:layer

That command will only show output from those three debug streams.

Wrapping Up

In many ways, Express is a lot like ASP.NET. That=E2=80=99s true not onl= y in how it handles HTTP traffic, but how it serves as a sort of =E2=80=9Cc= entral hub=E2=80=9D around which dozens (if not hundreds) of other packages= depend and extend. The =E2=80=9Cserve-static=E2=80=9D package, for example= , gives an Express app a pre-built way to serve up a directory for static (= that is, =E2=80=9Cnot executing on the server side=E2=80=9D) assets, like i= mages and fonts. In the next installment, I=E2=80=99ll start looking at how= to use the Express request and response objects. (If you can=E2=80=99t wai= t, check out the Express documentation at expressjs.com.) In the meantime =E2=80=A6 h= appy coding!

Ted Neward is the CTO at iTrellis, a consultin= g services company. He has written more than 100 articles and authored or c= o-authored a dozen books, including =E2=80=9CProfessional F# 2.0=E2=80=9D (= Wrox, 2010). He is an F# MVP and speaks at conferences around the world. He= consults and mentors regularly=E2=80=94reach him at ted@tedneward.com or ted@itrellis.com if you=E2=80=99re interested.

Thanks to the following technical expert for reviewing this article: Sha= wn Wildermuth
Shawn Wildermuth is a thirteen-time Microsoft MVP (ASP.NET/IIS), the author= of eight books and dozens of articles on software development, and a Plura= lsight author with over fifteen courses to his name. He is one of the Wilde= r Minds (htt= p://wilderminds.com) and can be reached at his blog at http://wildermuth.com.
